commText: So how long before Yashasvi Jaiswal gets that India cap? No pressure, selectors and no pressure, young man!! But if this is the trailer, then the Yashavi Jaiswal blockbuster is going to light up our television screen for a generation to come. Kudos to the IPL - where talent meets opportunity!! We can go off to bed early tonight thinking about that Jaiswal knock, but we'll be back tomorrow when MI host the champions Gujarat. Join us then, for now this is B0$signing off on behalf of B1$and B2$

B0$ This is always in my mind, to go out there and play well. It was a nice feeling today. It is not like everything I wanted happens, I prepare well and I trust in myself. I know the results will come. The winning shot was a great feeling, I wanted to finish the game and winning the game has been my motto. I'm blessed and grateful, I'm trying my best. (On whether he feels he missed out on a century) I think the net run rate was the only thing in our mind, me and Sanju were only talking about finishing the game quickly. (On the Buttler run out) I think it happens in the game, it gives me responsibility to do even better. And Sanju bhai came and said to keep playing my game, and not think about that run out. I'm just grateful for a tournament like the IPL where youngsters like me can come and perform. This has been a great platform for players like me to fulfill my dreams.

commText: B0$ I didn't have to do anything today. Just put bat on ball and watch him play. We are used to it now, even the bowlers know how he goes in the powerplay. He enjoys batting in the powerplay. (On Chahal) I think it is time to give him the tag of legend. We are grateful to have him in the franchise. Never have to speak to him, give him the ball and he knows what to do. He bowls at the death as well, very pleasing for me as a captain. (On the road ahead) We have two more quarter finals to play, the pressure in never off in the IPL. Each game, each over is important. You can sense how the atmosphere is when a legend like Jos Buttler throws his wicket away for Jaiswal. Very happy today but we have a few more matches to go.

B0$You have to praise his innings (on Jaiswal), it was a day when he could do anything he wanted. It was a 180 wicket as I said at the toss, our batting wasn't great and that's the result of us dropping 2 points. He was batting well right through the tournament, so I thought a part-time spinner could perhaps make him complacent, that was the plan, but he played superbly and those things do happen

commText: B0$ From time to time, there comes a player and there comes an innings that just makes you stop whatever you are doing, sit back and admire the brilliance on display. Today was such an innings, and Yashasvi Jaiswal is quickly becoming that sort of player who makes you pause from life - a generational talent!! This game was finished within the first over, when Jaiswal started the chase with two consecutive sixes off the first two balls. He then continued the onslaught against Harshit Rana, and then hit Shardul Thakur for a hat-trick of fours to secure the fastest fifty in IPL history. He got there in 13 balls, yes you read that correctly!! And he got there by playing pure cricketing shots, shots that had even the home ground stand up and clap in awe of the youngster. Sanju Samson played his role with a stroke filled 48 as well, as RR chased down the target with almost seven overs to spare. Anyone remember that Jos Buttler got out for a duck or a certain Joe Root is yet to bat in the IPL? RR were on a three match losing streak, but what a rousing reply this has been. Over to the presentations...

Thakur to Jaiswal, B0$, wide yorker, Jaiswal shuffles inwards and sweeps it through a vacant square leg region. Game, set, match but Jaiswal finishes two short of a century. Doesn't look like he was playing for that either way... he's overjoyed to get over the line and play this sort of innings

commText: B0$ Excellent bowling performance from the visitors after opting to bowl. Boult nipped out both the KKR openers, thanks to two good catches. Venkatesh Iyer and captain Nitish Rana steadied the ship somewhat after that. Venkatesh Iyer was slow to get off the blocks but he broke the shackles with successive sixes off Ashwin in the 10th over. At the halfway stage, the hosts were 76/2 and would have eyed a formidable total. But Chahal had other ideas. He removed Rana in his very first over and thereby became IPL's leading wicket-taker. He went for 15 in his 2nd over but came back strongly. Removed half-centurion Iyer and Thakur within a span of four deliveries and had the in-form Rinku Singh hole out. The legspinner choked KKR and finished with 4/25. Sandeep Sharma bowled two tight overs in the death and ensured that the Knight Riders didn't cross 150. Way too many dot balls and will that come back to haunt the home team? There's enough assistance for the spinners here but RR have a very good chance here to end their 3-match losing streak and jump to the third spot. Join us in a bit to find out how the action unfolds..

commText: B0$: (On his personal form) By God’s grace, things are going good for now but as a team we are all trying to do well each game, let’s see how today pans out. The seniors in the side keep telling me to trust myself, play good cricketing shots and take brave decisions. Their words motivate me to bat fearlessly. (On team atmosphere) It is always great with our dressing room and with Sanju (Samson). We enjoy playing together. A few ups and downs like these will keep happening, those are learnings for us, we keep learning to move forward.

B0$: (On the previous win) Quite calm, Rinku out there was doing the job for us, he's done it before. We are going out there in the last few games really enjoying ourselves and making the most of these occasions. The nerves were there for sure, but we're backing the young man. (Approaching today's game) It's not as simple as just kind of 'enjoying and going with the flow', it's individually looking ourselves in the mirror, seeing what mistakes we made at the start of the competition and rectifying them going forward for the rest of the competition. Last few games we've done that. Individually, the guys have come out, trained extremely hard and come out with clear plans. It's a nice dressing room to be part of at the moment, it seems relaxed and vibrant, looking forward to this occasion. I am happy for the young man (Rinku Singh), he's really kinda taken on that role and he's doing it incredibly well, excited to see what lies ahead for him. (On his own form) It's going okay, pretty happy with the starts I am getting. I am a big score away from feeling a million dollars. At the moment, it's just kinda getting in and building a good start for the team. I want those big scores. When I keep my game simple and I don't try too much, it's just as effective if not more effective than when I go over the top. I am just doing my thing, enjoying it, trying to find new ways of developing my game as well as helping others as well.

B0$: It's match 56 of the Indian Premier League and we're fast entering the final stages of the season. With 16 and 15 points respectively, Gujarat Titans and Chennai Super Kings, are pretty well placed. But there is a long logjam behind them with 5 teams in the range between 12 and 10 points. As such today's encounter between Kolkata Knight Riders and Rajasthan Royals is a big 4-pointer game from the tournament's perspective. Both have 10 points each and today's winner will directly vault onto the 3rd position, giving themselves a small but vital cushion. The Royals are coming off a 3-match losing streak while the Knight Riders are flying high, having won their last two games.

B0$    
    
"Arre sir, saral saral pooch lena."    
    
That was Rinku Singh on match eve, light-heartedly requesting the press to ask him easy questions, when he's had all the answers this season. The crowd at Eden Gardens knew it when they screamed "Rinku! Rinku!" in the middle of a tight finish against Punjab Kings. Andre Russell knew it in the same match when he ran a possible bye off the penultimate delivery and trusted Rinku with the finishing job. Kolkata Knight Riders, of course, have known it ever since acquiring his services in 2017.    
    
Rinku Singh will once again be in focus when KKR take on Rajasthan Royals at home. He will have happy memories of playing them too. His match-winning innings of 42* off 23 against RR last year won him his first Player-of-the-Match award in IPL and proved to be a turning point in his career at KKR, establishing him as one of their key players. Rinku hasn't missed a game for KKR ever since.    
    
While KKR go into this fixture with three wins in the last four games, it's lately been a jarring ride for RR who have lost five of their last six games. That they are still placed above KKR on the points table tells you how superlative their start of the season was.    
    
Now tasked with putting their campaign back on track, it wouldn't be an easy job for RR at the Eden Gardens, where the home side finally seemed to have cracked the winning formula after a tough initiation. A part of it was down to the slightly dry pitch KKR played on against PBKS, which brought their spinners more into play without compromising too much on the batting. The same pitch, where spinners picked 8/142 as compared to 3/211 by seamers, will be used for this game too and is likely to play to KKR's strengths again. RR, though, arrive with two of India's best spinners in their ranks and a batting line-up that wouldn't mind the bounce on offer either.    
    
As both teams play their third-last league game of the season, one is set to break away from the mid-table 10-pointer traffic jam. Who will be that, though, is hard to guess, and that's perhaps one question that even Rinku Singh might not have an answer to yet.    
    
B1$KKR vs RR on May 11, 2023 at 7:30 PM local    
    
B2$ Eden Gardens, Kolkata    
    
B3$The game will again be played on pitch #4, same as last night, which will make it the fourth IPL game to be played on the surface this season.    
    
With a deep depression forming in the Bay of Bengal owing to Cyclone Mocha, the conditions 24 hours out from the match were cloudy although it didn't rain and impede teams' practice. That, however, meant that the pitch once again wasn't watered much and is likely to have more in it for the slower bowlers this time around. Unequal ground dimensions on both sides (58 meters and 71 meters) is likely to once again heavily influence match tactics.    
    
No dew is expected although the last couple of games at the venue have been won by chasing sides. That will make for a tricky decision for Sanju Samson at the toss; RR have won only one out of their four games while chasing this season. No rain is forecast during the match but that could change quickly given the cyclonic conditions in the vicinity. The groundsmen covered the entire field of play on the eve of the match expecting overnight rain.

B5$    
    
Umesh Yadav, who has been sidelined with a minor left hamstring injury for the last three games, bowled with a full run-up on the eve of the match. He was seen bowling to Rinku Singh on the center practice wicket alongside other first-choice Varun Chakaravarthy, Andre Russell, Sunil Narine and Harshit Rana, with Vaibhav Arora not part of the drill. What that could mean is anybody's guess but that possible change aside, KKR are unlikely to tinker with a winning combination.    
    
B6$Nitish Rana has been one of the best players of spin in the last few editions of IPL but seems to struggle a bit against Yuzvendra Chahal, who has accounted for him five times in the past. This key battle will be crucial for both sides looking to get an important win under their belt. That said, KKR also have an ace in Sunil Narine against the opposition captain Sanju Samson, who's gotten out to the spinner thrice and scores against him at a modest strike-rate of 82.

B8$    
    
Trent Boult missed the last match with a niggle but should come right back into the Playing XI for this one. Expect them to play three spinners too on this track.    
    
B6$This year, RR have been one of the worst sides in the middle overs, losing as many as 32 wickets for only 749 runs from overs 7-15. That's got a lot to do with Shimron Hetmyer's dip in form, the batter totalling only 25 runs in his last six innings. How he and others in the middle-order fare against KKR's three-pronged spin attack could shape the match.
